    Mass Transport in High-Flux Hemodialysis: Application of Engineering Principles to Clinical Prescription.
In this review, engineering principles are applied to characterize the physical mechanisms behind the two major modes of mass transfer during hemodialysis, namely diffusion and convection. The manner in which flow rate, dialyzer geometry, and membrane microstructure affect these processes is discussed, with concepts such as boundary layers, effective membrane diffusivity, and sieving coefficients highlighted as critical considerations. The objective is to improve clinicians' understanding of these concepts as important factors influencing the prescription and delivery of hemodialysis therapy.
